  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Beyond Brumadinho: Curbing the Power of Brazil&#x2019;s Extractive Industries</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.	52 affected communities in the Paraopebas basin have their effective and informed participation in the negotiations and collective legal agreement processes ensured with a view to advance rights recognition. 
2.	Four at-risk communities in the state of Minas Gerais with increased preventive capacities are engaged in local advocacy for their rights.
3.	High-quality data and analysis is made available to breach information gaps and inform relevant stakeholders at the national and international level. 
4.	Civil Society Organizations (CSO) positions on tailing dams inform broader public and insider advocacy and are represented nationally in the implementation of relevant legislation and internationally in the Mining and Tailings Safety Initiative and the Global Tailings Review.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Main activities include a) direct support and follow up of affected communities in Brumadinho and the development of participatory risk assessments in at least other four at-risk areas in Brazil; b) legal follow up of collective agreements ; c) local, national and international advocacy regarding mining sector regulation; d) data gathering and assessments to inform national and international advocacy; e) International outreach to keep momentum and develop coordinated initiatives in support of Brumadinho victims and to ensure full accountability from Vale.</narrative>
  </description>
